comment.body:
I agree that that's a much better design pattern, however `dbt` doesn't support code reuse from a dbt project. It's a requested feature yet to be implemented: https://docs.getdbt.com/docs/build/python-models#code-reuse 

A work around is to create a private python library, have our databricks cluster install that private library, then run our cleaner code. The cost is maintenance of that library.

IMO as our data workflows scale in number and complexity, bringing in Airflow for this type of task is best suited. This PR is for part of a custom ingestion job that Airbyte can't handle on it's own, and it's a job that  databricks/spark/pyspark isn't optimized for (I tried delegating mini batches of States to different spark workers but the long SFTP downloads were unstable on those workers).

issue.title: feature: support custom package providers
issue.body:
I want to install a package that doesn't provide a GitHub release but is available through a pattern-based URL including the package version.

For example, the AWS CLI is available via pattern `https://awscli.amazonaws.com/AWSCLIV2-{version}.pkg` ([docs](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/cli/latest/userguide/getting-started-version.html))

Ideally I could configure a custom provider that includes the URL pattern, and I could reference this provider to install new versions of the package.

Example config:
```
custom_providers:
  - name: aws
    url_pattern: https://awscli.amazonaws.com/AWSCLIV2-{version}.pkg
```

Example usage:
```
$ dist install custom/aws@2.27.12
```

comment.body:
I thought a little about that. For example, let's look at `kubectl`.

For version 1.31.8, the client download URLs are [here](https://github.com/kubernetes/kubernetes/blob/master/CHANGELOG/CHANGELOG-1.31.md#downloads-for-v1318).
The pattern appears to be: `https://dl.k8s.io/v{version}/kubernetes-client-{os}-{arch}.tar.gz`
For Mac with Apple Silicon, the download URL is: https://dl.k8s.io/v1.31.8/kubernetes-client-darwin-arm64.tar.gz

The _simplest_ option would be to just bake the OS and architecture into the URL pattern. This config would work for an individual user but wouldn't be cross-platform. For example, I could set the pattern to `https://dl.k8s.io/v{version}/kubernetes-client-darwin-arm64.tar.gz` and it would work for a Mac with Apple Silicon. This doesn't seem too bad for a first pass.

If you wanted a config that worked for multiple platforms/architectures, you might need some mapping in the config to map the OS/ARCH detected by Distillery to the strings used by the URL pattern.

```
custom_providers:
  - name: aws
    url_pattern: https://some-custom-package-registry/my-package-{os}-{arch}-{version}.pkg
    # Maps detected GOOS value to specific string
    os_mapping:
      darwin: mac
      windows: win
    # Maps detected GOARCH value to specific string
    arch_mapping:
      arm64: arm
      amd64: x64
```
